            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers visiting a friend's startup in SoMa around 1999. The loft smelled of stale pizza and manic optimism, the coders fuelled by Red Bull. Standing there in his bank-approved slacks, Adam felt a profound sense of alienation, not envy. He saw the gamble, the chaotic faith in something intangible. Driving back across the bridge, he felt a quiet certainty in his choice for structure over chaos. It was the moment he committed to being the financier, not the founder, cementing a risk-averse nature that would define his career.\n\n2.\nHis father, the auto mechanic, visited his high-rise office for the first time about ten years ago. He ran a calloused hand over the cool marble of the reception desk, looking out the panoramic window at the city below. \u201cYou did good, mijo,\u201d he\u2019d said, his voice full of pride. But Adam saw the faint unease in his eyes\u2014the look of a man who understood engines, not abstract capital. In that moment, Adam felt the immense distance he had traveled from his roots, a success measured by how different his hands were from his father\u2019s.\n\n3.\nEight years ago, after the last of his ex-wife\u2019s boxes were gone, he stood in the cavernous living room of their Marin home. The silence was deafening, a physical pressure where family life used to be. He noticed how the afternoon light illuminated dust motes in the empty air. This wasn't freedom; it was an echo chamber. He called a realtor the next day. The dense, anonymous energy of a city condo, he decided, was the only thing loud enough to drown out that specific quiet.\n\n4.\nIt was three years ago, at a celebratory dinner at a posh Financial District steakhouse after closing the Landmark Tower deal. The wine was obscenely expensive, the laughter loud. He should have felt triumphant. Instead, he found himself watching a couple at another table sharing a quiet joke. The deal felt distant, a set of numbers on a page. The victory was hollow, a temporary high that left him feeling profoundly alone. It was the first time fulfillment felt more important than achievement.\n\n5.\nLast season, during a tight Warriors game at the Chase Center, he was completely absorbed. But during a timeout, he glanced at the couple next to him. They weren't watching the Jumbotron; the man was just brushing a stray hair from her face. It was a tiny, insignificant gesture. For Adam, it eclipsed the entire game. The roar of the crowd faded, replaced by a sudden, sharp ache for a connection that had nothing to do with a scoreboard or a balance sheet."
